I wasn't quite right. `fill_event` modifies in place and returns nothing, so this is not possible in one line.

```python
def get_filtered_events(*args, **kwargs):
     for ev for ev in get_events(*args, fill=False, **kwargs):
        if ...:
            fill_event(ev)
            yield ev
```

This suggests to me that it would be better if `fill_event` returned the instance of the event that it modified in place. Recent discussion has indicated that `fill_event` is problematic in other ways as well -- maybe needs a re-think.

